(p There was something in Perry Robinson‚Äôs tone that made Frank and Joe extremely sorry for their chum, for it seemed that the boy realized that the case looked black against his father.)
(p Although the Hardy lads realized that it was only natural that Perry should stand up for his father, they shared some of his conviction that Mr.¬†Robinson was not guilty.)
(p ‚ÄúOf course he‚Äôs innocent,‚Äù agreed Frank. ‚ÄúHe‚Äôll be able to clear himself all right, Perry.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúBut everything looks pretty black against him,‚Äù said Perry, who was pale and shaken. ‚ÄúUnless your father can catch the real thief I‚Äôm afraid Dad will be blamed for it.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúEverybody knows your father is honest,‚Äù said Joe consolingly. ‚ÄúHe has a good record‚Å†‚Äîeven Applegate will have to admit that.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúA good record won‚Äôt help him very much if he is blamed for this and can‚Äôt clear himself. And Dad admits that he did know the combination of the safe.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúHe knew it?‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúAccidentally. He was cleaning the library fireplace one day when he found a slip of paper with numbers marked on it. The combination was so simple that anyone could remember it if he read it once. Dad didn‚Äôt realize what it was until he had studied it a while, and then he put it back on Mr.¬†Applegate‚Äôs desk. The window was open and the breeze had blown the paper to the floor.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúDoes Applegate know that?‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúNot yet. But Dad is going to tell him now. He says he knows it will look bad for him, but he‚Äôs going to tell the truth about it. He knew the combination, although of course he would never think of using it.‚Äù)
(p From the library came the dull hum of voices. The harsh tones of Hurd Applegate occasionally rose above the murmur of conversation and once the boys heard Mr.¬†Robinson‚Äôs voice rise sharply.)
(p ‚ÄúI (em didn‚Äôt) do it. I tell you I (em didn‚Äôt) take that money.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúThen where did you get the nine hundred you paid on that note?‚Äù demanded Mr.¬†Applegate.)
(p There was silence for a while.)
(p ‚ÄúWhere did you get it?‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúI‚Äôm not at liberty to tell you.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúYou won‚Äôt tell?‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúI can‚Äôt.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúWhy not?‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúI got the money honestly‚Å†‚Äîthat‚Äôs all I can say about it.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúOh, ho!‚Äù exclaimed Applegate. ‚ÄúYou got the money honestly, yet you can‚Äôt tell me where it came from! That‚Äôs very likely, isn‚Äôt it? If you got it honestly you shouldn‚Äôt be ashamed to tell where you got it.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúI‚Äôm not ashamed. But I‚Äôm not at liberty to tell.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúMighty funny thing that you should get nine hundred dollars so quickly. You were pretty hard up last week, weren‚Äôt you? Had to ask for an advance on your month‚Äôs wages.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúI admit it.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúAnd then the day of this robbery you suddenly have nine hundred dollars that you can‚Äôt explain.‚Äù)
(p Mr.¬†Hardy‚Äôs calm voice broke in.)
(p ‚ÄúOf course, I don‚Äôt like to pry into your private affairs, Mr.¬†Robinson,‚Äù he said; ‚Äúbut it would be best if you could clear up this matter of the money. You must admit yourself that it doesn‚Äôt look promising.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúI know it looks bad,‚Äù replied the caretaker doggedly. ‚ÄúBut I can‚Äôt tell you where that money came from.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúAnd you admit knowing the combination of the safe, too!‚Äù broke in Applegate. ‚ÄúI didn‚Äôt know that before. Why didn‚Äôt you tell me?‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúI didn‚Äôt consider it important enough. I had found the combination by accident and I had no intention of using it. As a matter of fact, I don‚Äôt think I could remember it accurately right now. I just put the paper back and decided to say nothing about it, to save trouble.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúAnd yet you come and tell me about it now!‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúI have nothing to conceal. If I had taken the money I wouldn‚Äôt very likely be telling you now that I knew the combination.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúYes,‚Äù agreed Mr.¬†Hardy, ‚Äúthat‚Äôs a point in your favor.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúIs it?‚Äù asked Applegate. ‚ÄúYou‚Äôre just clever enough to think up a trick like that, Robinson. You think that if you come to me now and admit you knew the combination I‚Äôll believe that you are so honest that you couldn‚Äôt have committed this robbery. Very clever. But not clever enough. There‚Äôs enough evidence right here and now to convict you, and I‚Äôm not going to delay another minute.‚Äù)
(p There was the sound of a telephone receiver being lifted, and then Applegate‚Äôs voice continued‚Å†‚Äî)
(p ‚ÄúPolice station.‚Äù After a short wait, he went on. ‚ÄúHello‚Å†‚Äîpolice station?‚Å†‚ÄîThis is Applegate speaking‚Å†‚ÄîApplegate‚Å†‚ÄîHurd Applegate.‚Å†‚ÄîWell, I think we‚Äôve found our man.‚Å†‚ÄîIn that robbery.‚Å†‚ÄîYes, Robinson.‚Å†‚ÄîYou thought so, eh?‚Å†‚ÄîSo did I, but I wasn‚Äôt sure.‚Å†‚ÄîHe has practically convicted himself by his own story.‚Å†‚ÄîYes, I want him arrested.‚Å†‚ÄîYou‚Äôll be up right away?‚Å†‚ÄîFine.‚Å†‚ÄîGoodbye.‚Äù)
(p The telephone tinkled.)
(p ‚ÄúYou‚Äôre not going to have me arrested, Mr.¬†Applegate?‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúWhy not? You took the money!‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúBut I‚Äôm innocent! I swear it! Haven‚Äôt I always been honest, ever since I came to work for you? Have you ever had any fault to find with me?‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúNot until now,‚Äù returned Applegate grimly.)
(p ‚ÄúIt might have been better to wait a while,‚Äù suggested Mr.¬†Hardy mildly. ‚ÄúOf course, it is entirely in your hands, Mr.¬†Applegate, and I admit the case looks rather bad against Mr.¬†Robinson. But perhaps some more evidence may turn up.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúWhat more evidence do we want? The man‚Äôs guilty. It‚Äôs as plain as the nose on your face. If he wants to return the rest of the jewels and securities I‚Äôll see what can be done toward having the charge reduced‚Å†‚Äîbut that‚Äôs all.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúBut I can‚Äôt return them! I didn‚Äôt take them!‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúI suppose you have them hidden safely away by now, hoping to get them when you get out of penitentiary, eh? It‚Äôll be a long time, Robinson‚Å†‚Äîa long time.‚Äù)
(p In the hallway, the boys listened in growing excitement. The case had taken an abrupt and tragic turn. Both the Hardy boys were sorry for their chum Slim, who looked as though he might collapse under the strain.)
(p ‚ÄúHe‚Äôs innocent,‚Äù muttered the boy, over and over again. ‚ÄúI (em know) he‚Äôs innocent. They can‚Äôt arrest him. My dad never stole a dollar in his life!‚Äù)
(p Frank patted him on the shoulder.)
(p ‚ÄúBrace up, old chap,‚Äù he advised. ‚ÄúIt looks pretty bad just now, but your father will be able to clear himself, never fear.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúI‚Å†‚ÄîI‚Äôll have to tell mother‚Å†‚Äî,‚Äù stammered Slim. ‚ÄúThis will break her heart. And my sisters‚Å†‚Äî‚Äù)
(p Frank and Joe led him down through the hallway and along a corridor that led to a wing of the mansion, where the Robinson family had rooms. There, in a neat, but sparsely furnished apartment, they found Mrs.¬†Robinson, a gentle, kindly-faced woman, somewhat lame, who was sitting anxiously in a chair by the window. Her two daughters, Paula and Tessie, twins, were by her side, and all looked up in expectation as the lads came in.)
(p ‚ÄúWhat news, son?‚Äù asked Mrs.¬†Robinson bravely, after she had greeted the Hardy boys.)
(p ‚ÄúBad, mother.‚Äù)
(p ‚ÄúThey‚Äôre not‚Å†‚Äîthey‚Äôre not‚Å†‚Äîarresting him?‚Äù cried Paula, springing forward.)
(p Perry nodded, dumbly.)
(p ‚ÄúBut they can‚Äôt!‚Äù cried Tessie protestingly. ‚ÄúHe‚Äôs innocent! He (em couldn‚Äôt) do anything like that! It‚Äôs wrong‚Å†‚Äî‚Äù)
(p Mrs.¬†Robinson began to cry, quite silently. Perry went over to his mother and awkwardly patted her shoulder, his face white and stern. The twins gazed at one another with desperate eyes.)
(p Frank and Joe, their hearts too full for utterance, withdrew softly from the room.)
